This is actually a **production-style CI/CD pipeline**. I'll explain it like an interviewer would expect you to understand it—not just what each line does, but **why it's used**.

---

# Job Definition

```yaml
build-and-ship:
```

This is the name of the job.

The pipeline has three jobs:

1. Quality & Security Checks
2. Unit Tests
3. **Build and Ship Docker Image** ← this job

---

# Runner

```yaml
runs-on: ubuntu-latest
```

GitHub creates a fresh Ubuntu virtual machine.

Think of it as:

```
GitHub
     ↓
Creates Ubuntu Server
     ↓
Runs all these commands
     ↓
Deletes the server
```

Every workflow run gets a brand-new machine.

---

# Dependency

```yaml
needs: unit-tests
```

Means:

```
Quality Checks
       ↓
Unit Tests
       ↓
Build Docker Image
```

If unit tests fail,

```
Build Job
❌ Won't even start
```

This prevents deploying broken code.

---

# Run only on Push to Main

```yaml
if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main' && github.event_name == 'push'
```

Suppose someone creates a Pull Request.

```
feature/login
      ↓
Pull Request
```

The Docker image **will NOT** be pushed.

Only when:

```
Merge
     ↓
main branch
     ↓
Push Event
```

does this job execute.

This avoids publishing Docker images for every feature branch.

---

# Checkout Code

```yaml
uses: actions/checkout@v6
```

Downloads your repository into the GitHub runner.

Before:

```
Runner
(empty)
```

After:

```
Runner

/app
   package.json
   Dockerfile
   src/
```

Without this step, nothing exists to build.

---

# Setup Buildx

```yaml
uses: docker/setup-buildx-action@v3
```

This enables Docker Buildx.

Buildx provides:

* Faster builds
* Multi-stage builds
* Build cache
* Multi-architecture images

Without Buildx:

```
docker build
```

With Buildx:

```
docker buildx build
```

Almost every modern CI pipeline uses Buildx.

---

# Docker Login

```yaml
uses: docker/login-action@v3
```

with

```yaml
username:
password:
```

GitHub logs into Docker Hub.

Equivalent to running:

```bash
docker login
```

Without login,

```
docker push
```

would fail with

```
unauthorized
```

because Docker Hub requires authentication.

---

# Build Docker Image

```yaml
uses: docker/build-push-action@v5
```

with

```yaml
context: .
```

means

```
Use current directory
```

which contains

```
Dockerfile
package.json
src/
```

---

## load: true

```yaml
load: true
```

This is extremely important.

Normally Buildx builds inside an isolated builder.

```
Builder
    ↓
Creates image
```

But the local Docker daemon cannot see it.

With

```yaml
load: true
```

the image is copied into Docker on the runner.

```
Builder
      ↓
Docker Engine
      ↓
Available locally
```

Now Trivy can scan it.

Without

```yaml
load: true
```

Trivy would report:

```
Image not found
```

---

# Image Tag

```yaml
tags:
myuser/ci-cd-pipeline-demo:latest
```

creates

```
Repository

ci-cd-pipeline-demo

Tag

latest
```

Exactly like

```bash
docker build \
-t myuser/ci-cd-pipeline-demo:latest .
```

---

# Trivy Scan

```yaml
uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action
```

Trivy is a security scanner.

It checks

```
Docker Image
```

for

* OS vulnerabilities

Example

```
openssl
glibc
busybox
```

and

* Application packages

Example

```
express
axios
lodash
undici
```

---

# Image to Scan

```yaml
image-ref:
```

You're telling Trivy

```
Scan this image

myuser/ci-cd-pipeline-demo:latest
```

---

# Output Format

```yaml
format: table
```

Instead of JSON

```
{
...
}
```

it prints

```
Library
Severity
Version
Fix Version
```

which is much easier to read.

---

# exit-code

Originally

```yaml
exit-code: '1'
```

means

```
If HIGH or CRITICAL found

↓

Pipeline Failed
```

You changed it to

```yaml
exit-code: '0'
```

Meaning

```
Found vulnerability?

↓

Report it

↓

Continue pipeline
```

This is useful for demos.

---

# ignore-unfixed

```yaml
ignore-unfixed: true
```

Suppose

```
openssl

HIGH

No fix exists yet
```

Should Trivy fail?

```
No
```

because developers cannot fix something that has no available patch.

Only vulnerabilities with an available fix are considered.

---

# vuln-type

```yaml
vuln-type:
os,library
```

Means scan

Operating System

```
Alpine Linux

BusyBox

OpenSSL
```

and

Application packages

```
Node Modules

Python Packages

Java Libraries
```

---

# severity

```yaml
severity:
CRITICAL,HIGH
```

Ignore

```
LOW

MEDIUM
```

Report only

```
HIGH

CRITICAL
```

because these are the most serious.

---

# Push Image

```yaml
docker/build-push-action
```

again.

Why twice?

Because the first build was

```
Build

↓

Local

↓

Scan
```

The second build is

```
Build

↓

Push

↓

Docker Hub
```

---

# push

```yaml
push: true
```

Equivalent to

```bash
docker push
```

Without this,

the image stays only inside the GitHub runner.

---

# Multiple Tags

```yaml
tags:

latest

github.sha
```

This pushes **two versions**.

### Tag 1

```
latest
```

Always points to the newest image.

```
latest

↓

Image v15
```

---

### Tag 2

```yaml
${{ github.sha }}
```

Example

```
8f71bc92a0
```

Every commit gets its own unique image.

```
myuser/app

latest

8f71bc92a0

b56c97a31f

cc78d22ee8
```

This is important because if production breaks after a deployment, you can roll back to a known-good image simply by deploying the previous commit's tag instead of rebuilding.

---

# Complete Flow

```
Developer Pushes Code
        │
        ▼
Checkout Repository
        │
        ▼
Setup Docker Buildx
        │
        ▼
Login to Docker Hub
        │
        ▼
Build Docker Image
(load locally)
        │
        ▼
Run Trivy Scan
        │
        ├── Vulnerabilities found?
        │         │
        │         ├── exit-code=1 → Pipeline fails
        │         └── exit-code=0 → Continue
        ▼
Build & Push Image
        │
        ▼
Docker Hub
        ├── latest
        └── <commit SHA>
```

## Interview explanation

If an interviewer asks, "Why build the image twice?", a good answer is:

> "The first build uses `load: true` so the image is available on the GitHub runner for Trivy to scan before it's published. After the scan passes—or is allowed to continue in a demo setup—the second `docker/build-push-action` builds and pushes the image to Docker Hub with both the `latest` tag and a unique commit SHA tag. The SHA tag provides immutable versioning and makes rollbacks straightforward."
